The soldiers in ‘Exposure’ are shown to be unable to do anything to improve
their situation. They are described as cringing “in holes”, creating an image of
the soldiers as helpless and crippled by fear. This reects how trench warfare in
the First World War left soldiers shellshocked and psychologically traumatised.
Likewise, in ‘Belfast Confetti’, the speaker’s helplessness is shown through rhetorical
questions such as “Why can’t I escape?” — this shows their physical entrapment
in the streets and their inability to escape. Listing Belfast street names, such as
“Balaclava, Raglan, Inkerman”, helps to situate the conict in an everyday Belfast
setting, showing how the Troubles made ordinary people feel helpless.
‘Exposure’ and ‘Belfast Confetti’ both present vividly negative views of
the reality of conict. The experience of the speakers in the two poems is very
different: Owen focuses on the hopelessness and passive suffering of men dying
from exposure, whereas Carson focuses on the panicked confusion of a person
experiencing a bomb explosion. However, both poets use structure, form and vivid
imagery to powerfully convey suffering. The speakers show a feeling of helplessness
when faced with conict, showing the bleak and dehumanising reality of conict.
